1
00:00:40,540 --> 00:00:42,735
More than three
thousand years ago,

2
00:00:42,775 --> 00:00:46,768
a man named Job complained to
God about all his troubles.

3
00:00:47,480 --> 00:00:50,711
And the Bible tells
us that God answered.

4
00:00:51,417 --> 00:00:54,352
Do you give the
horse his strength?

5
00:00:54,387 --> 00:00:56,947
Or clothe his neck
with a flowing mane?

6
00:00:57,857 --> 00:01:00,553
Do you make him
leap like a locust,

7
00:01:00,593 --> 00:01:03,494
striking terror with
his proud snorting?

8
00:01:05,064 --> 00:01:09,558
He paws fiercely,
rejoicing in his strength

9
00:01:09,602 --> 00:01:11,832
and charges into the fray.

10
00:01:11,871 --> 00:01:14,396
He laughs at fear,
afraid of nothing.

11
00:01:15,441 --> 00:01:17,636
He does not shy away
from the sword.

12
00:01:18,411 --> 00:01:20,743
The quiver rattles
against his side,

13
00:01:20,780 --> 00:01:23,271
along with the flashing
spear and lance.

14
00:01:23,850 --> 00:01:27,013
In frenzied excitement
he eats up the ground.

15
00:01:27,653 --> 00:01:31,180
He cannot stand still
when the trumpet sounds.

16
00:01:51,377 --> 00:01:54,244
Kate, Sarah, you have to
leave in ten minutes.

17
00:01:54,280 --> 00:01:58,080
Penny, I have three shirts
to pick up at the cleaners,

18
00:01:58,117 --> 00:02:00,585
and two more to go in the
hamper, if you wouldn't mind.

19
00:02:00,620 --> 00:02:02,986
- I'll pick those up.
- Also go by the wine shop,

20
00:02:03,022 --> 00:02:04,754
pick up some Riesling?
I have a client

21
00:02:04,755 --> 00:02:06,219
coming in. That's all he drinks.

22
00:02:06,259 --> 00:02:07,817
Sarah, orange juice, please.

23
00:02:07,860 --> 00:02:11,125
- No nuclear devices on the table.
- Come on, Dad.

24
00:02:11,164 --> 00:02:12,631
Daddy, I need to pick up a gown.

25
00:02:12,665 --> 00:02:14,155
Another gown?

26
00:02:14,200 --> 00:02:16,964
When you earn your own money, you
can buy gowns for every party.

27
00:02:17,003 --> 00:02:18,558
I'm sure we can find something

28
00:02:18,559 --> 00:02:20,734
reasonable. We can go
look this weekend.

29
00:02:20,773 --> 00:02:22,418
Not Gewürztraminer, only Riesling.

30
00:02:22,419 --> 00:02:23,708
Mum, can we have pancakes?

31
00:02:23,743 --> 00:02:26,234
- Working on it.
- Che Guevara or Ho Chi Minh?

32
00:02:26,279 --> 00:02:27,443
What are you doing?

33
00:02:27,444 --> 00:02:29,771
Getting ready for a
Christmas pageant.

34
00:02:29,816 --> 00:02:32,410
- A Christmas pageant? When?
- Spring.

35
00:02:32,452 --> 00:02:36,183
It's experimental. Has to do with
Christmas and lots of things.

36
00:02:36,222 --> 00:02:38,952
Really? That's great.
What's the role?

37
00:02:38,991 --> 00:02:42,324
- The War Protester.
- I was thinking that we could...

38
00:02:42,361 --> 00:02:44,329
- The what?
- The War Protester.

39
00:02:45,731 --> 00:02:48,791
It's a really good role, Mum.
You'll love it. You, too, Dad.

40
00:02:48,835 --> 00:02:51,039
Tweedy residence. This is she.

41
00:02:51,040 --> 00:02:53,863
War protester in a
Christmas pageant?

42
00:02:59,479 --> 00:03:02,243
We'll leave this
afternoon. Thank you.

43
00:03:20,967 --> 00:03:24,698
What are you doing? I don't pay
you to dream, I pay you to work.

44
00:03:24,804 --> 00:03:28,240
Now, let's get to it. Come on.
You do that on your own time.

45
00:03:29,742 --> 00:03:33,542
Thank you.

46
00:03:33,579 --> 00:03:34,876
Oh, Hollis.

47
00:03:41,153 --> 00:03:42,745
Mama's gone.

48
00:03:44,190 --> 00:03:47,159
She's gone. Hi, Jack.

49
00:03:47,260 --> 00:03:49,512
Hollis, I'm so sorry
for your loss.

50
00:03:49,513 --> 00:03:51,890
Your mother was
always so kind to me.

51
00:03:55,835 --> 00:03:58,804
- Miss Chenery, we're sorry.
- Thank you.

52
00:04:04,277 --> 00:04:05,801
Penny...

53
00:04:05,845 --> 00:04:08,313
Penny, darling. Darling.

54
00:04:11,951 --> 00:04:14,647
Girls, you remember Miss
Ham? Granddaddy's secretary?

55
00:04:14,687 --> 00:04:17,952
- Hi, Miss Ham.
- Oh, my, you two have grown.

56
00:04:19,191 --> 00:04:21,955
Thank you so much, Miss
Ham. For everything.

57
00:04:24,230 --> 00:04:26,164
Hollis said you found her.

58
00:04:26,198 --> 00:04:30,100
She had just fallen. The
doctor said she didn't suffer.

59
00:04:30,136 --> 00:04:34,232
She looked... peaceful.

60
00:04:36,208 --> 00:04:37,698
How is Daddy?

61
00:04:40,813 --> 00:04:42,713
He keeps asking, Where is she?

62
00:04:42,748 --> 00:04:46,844
But I'm not sure if he's
asking for your mother or you.

63
00:04:49,889 --> 00:04:53,086
Girls, I'm going to go in and
see your granddaddy now.

64
00:04:53,960 --> 00:04:55,985
I'll bring you in later.

65
00:04:56,028 --> 00:04:58,997
Come on, girls. Let's get
you something to eat.

66
00:05:01,701 --> 00:05:03,498
Don't let them fool you, darling.

67
00:05:06,706 --> 00:05:09,607
It's not whether
they think we won.

68
00:05:09,642 --> 00:05:12,202
It's whether we think we won.

69
00:05:15,548 --> 00:05:17,948
You run your race, Penny.

70
00:05:28,761 --> 00:05:29,853
We'll take 'em.

71
00:05:31,664 --> 00:05:34,132
We just got ourselves
a couple new horses.

72
00:05:34,166 --> 00:05:36,191
Are we going to race them?

73
00:05:36,235 --> 00:05:37,964
No.

74
00:05:38,004 --> 00:05:41,201
They're going to be mommies
and daddies for new horses.

75
00:05:46,879 --> 00:05:47,903
Helen?

76
00:05:49,281 --> 00:05:52,250
Daddy, it's Penny.

77
00:05:54,186 --> 00:05:55,448
Penny.

78
00:05:57,023 --> 00:05:58,718
You got married.

79
00:06:00,059 --> 00:06:01,219
Yes.

80
00:06:04,463 --> 00:06:06,090
But I'm here now.

81
00:06:08,834 --> 00:06:12,429
Because Mama's gone.

82
00:06:26,018 --> 00:06:27,508
Mama's pin?

83
00:06:30,322 --> 00:06:32,051
Yours now.

84
00:06:37,163 --> 00:06:38,255
Daddy.

85
00:06:38,297 --> 00:06:42,324
The Lord shall preserve thy
going out, and thy coming in.

86
00:06:42,368 --> 00:06:44,097
From this time forth...

87
00:06:44,870 --> 00:06:46,929
and even forever more.

88
00:06:46,972 --> 00:06:51,432
And so we return to You your
faithful servant, Helen Chenery.

89
00:06:51,477 --> 00:06:53,911
Loving mother, devoted wife...

90
00:06:54,647 --> 00:06:57,377
who lived each moment
to the fullest,

91
00:06:57,416 --> 00:07:00,510
cherishing the life she had with
her beloved husband, Christopher.

92
00:07:00,553 --> 00:07:03,647
And may the peace that
passeth all understanding

93
00:07:03,689 --> 00:07:07,090
be in your hearts now
and forever more.

94
00:07:07,126 --> 00:07:09,287
- Amen.
- Amen.

95
00:07:14,100 --> 00:07:18,628
Eddie? Eddie, I just wanted to
thank you so much for coming.

96
00:07:19,305 --> 00:07:21,870
Miss Penny, your mama
was a fine woman.

97
00:07:21,871 --> 00:07:24,242
I just feel real bad
for Mr Chenery.

98
00:07:24,744 --> 00:07:26,439
He always thought
the world of you.

99
00:07:26,479 --> 00:07:28,959
He said you could hear the horses'
thoughts through your hands.

100
00:07:30,015 --> 00:07:33,451
Yeah, well, your father's
a good man, Miss Penny.

101
00:07:33,486 --> 00:07:34,578
Thank you.

102
00:07:37,256 --> 00:07:38,985
Mrs Tweedy?

103
00:07:40,025 --> 00:07:41,652
I'm Arthur Hancock.

104
00:07:41,694 --> 00:07:43,457
- Your daddy called me...
- Bull.

105
00:07:43,496 --> 00:07:45,794
Oh, yes, and everyone else
did, too, as I recall.

106
00:07:45,831 --> 00:07:47,696
This is my son, Seth.

107
00:07:47,733 --> 00:07:50,099
- Hi, nice to meet you.
- Thank you for coming.

108
00:07:50,136 --> 00:07:53,765
Your mother was a fine woman. It
was a privilege just knowing her.

109
00:07:53,806 --> 00:07:54,898
Thank you.

110
00:07:55,007 --> 00:07:57,498
I know you're going to
be making some changes,

111
00:07:57,543 --> 00:07:59,477
and if you or your family have any

112
00:07:59,478 --> 00:08:01,639
questions, Miss Ham's
got my number.

113
00:08:01,680 --> 00:08:02,908
Thank you, Bull.

114
00:08:06,218 --> 00:08:07,242
Ma'am...

115
00:08:08,821 --> 00:08:12,313
Your daddy's eyes would always
light up when he talked about you.

116
00:08:13,359 --> 00:08:16,954
How smart you are. How
much you loved the horses.

117
00:08:26,939 --> 00:08:29,169
Doctor says there may
be some brief moments

118
00:08:29,208 --> 00:08:32,200
when he is aware of things,
but we shouldn't expect much.

119
00:08:32,244 --> 00:08:36,203
Practical thing would be to
put him in a nursing home.

120
00:08:36,248 --> 00:08:41,413
This is home to him. And
he knows he's here.

121
00:08:41,453 --> 00:08:43,655
I think as long as
he does, we should

122
00:08:43,656 --> 00:08:45,856
hire nurses and let
him stay at home.

123
00:08:45,891 --> 00:08:50,225
The farm has to go. And
it won't bring much.

124
00:08:50,262 --> 00:08:54,631
It's been losing money hand
over fist for years now.

125
00:08:54,667 --> 00:08:59,036
We have to face facts. To run
a horse breeding operation,

126
00:08:59,071 --> 00:09:00,902
you need a certain touch.

127
00:09:00,940 --> 00:09:03,568
I'm a professor, and
you're a housewife.

128
00:09:04,610 --> 00:09:06,434
I moved up our flight
to first thing

129
00:09:06,435 --> 00:09:08,011
tomorrow. I've got to get back.

130
00:09:09,048 --> 00:09:11,039
Jack, I need a few more days here.

131
00:09:11,083 --> 00:09:13,526
I have to make sure Daddy's all

132
00:09:13,527 --> 00:09:16,521
right, sort through
Mother's things.

133
00:09:16,555 --> 00:09:19,046
The kids could all do with
a little responsibility.

134
00:09:19,091 --> 00:09:20,581
It will just be a few days.

135
00:09:20,626 --> 00:09:24,892
We need to file right away
for his power of attorney?

136
00:09:24,930 --> 00:09:28,331
Miss Ham says he tried to sell
four of his best horses last month

137
00:09:28,367 --> 00:09:31,331
for half of what
they're worth. Mum had

138
00:09:31,332 --> 00:09:33,999
to step in and stop
him, and now...

139
00:09:34,039 --> 00:09:36,701
I suppose someone will have to
clean up for the liquidation.

140
00:09:37,977 --> 00:09:40,167
Hollis, if you need
any help on the

141
00:09:40,168 --> 00:09:42,175
tax issues you call me, anytime.

142
00:09:43,515 --> 00:09:45,915
Thanks, Jack. It will
just be for a few days.

143
00:09:50,122 --> 00:09:52,283
Sarah makes great pancakes.

144
00:09:52,324 --> 00:09:54,588
- Oh, no.
- They're toxic. We won't survive.

145
00:09:54,627 --> 00:09:56,322
That's right, you won't.

146
00:09:56,362 --> 00:09:58,922
Make sure Hollis has that
power of attorney order.

147
00:09:59,665 --> 00:10:02,259
- The estate's vulnerable.
- I will. I'll stay on him.

148
00:10:03,002 --> 00:10:05,493
Mum, give Granddaddy a hug
for us when he wakes up.

149
00:10:05,537 --> 00:10:08,404
- I will. I love you.
- Love you.

150
00:10:08,440 --> 00:10:10,101
- Bye, Mum.
- Be good.

151
00:10:10,142 --> 00:10:11,234
We will.

152
00:10:26,659 --> 00:10:32,029
Miss Ham. Thank you.

153
00:10:32,064 --> 00:10:34,055
Two sugars and cream?

154
00:10:34,099 --> 00:10:35,259
How did you know?

155
00:10:35,301 --> 00:10:38,498
- It's how your daddy likes it.
- Oh.

156
00:10:39,972 --> 00:10:41,462
You doing all right, honey?

157
00:10:42,274 --> 00:10:43,400
Yes.

158
00:10:45,678 --> 00:10:48,670
No. But I'll be all right.

159
00:10:53,152 --> 00:10:55,313
These two are both
pregnant by Bold Ruler.

160
00:10:57,990 --> 00:11:01,551
And great colts come
from great sires.

161
00:11:04,596 --> 00:11:05,654
Miss Ham?

162
00:11:07,132 --> 00:11:09,293
My mother thought
the world of you.

163
00:11:09,335 --> 00:11:14,432
And my father's trust in
you was... is absolute.

164
00:11:14,473 --> 00:11:16,338
I hope you'll stay.

165
00:11:17,509 --> 00:11:20,034
Funny, I was about to
tell you the same thing.

166
00:11:20,079 --> 00:11:22,547
Al. Who the hell told you
to bring this one out?

167
00:11:22,581 --> 00:11:25,072
The sable, put it back. Bring
out the yearling in 18.

168
00:11:25,117 --> 00:11:27,847
- Yes, sir, Mister Jansen.
- Who are you?

169
00:11:29,121 --> 00:11:31,214
Penny Tweedy.

170
00:11:31,256 --> 00:11:34,419
- Penny Chenery.
- Oh, you're the daughter.

171
00:11:35,160 --> 00:11:40,120
- Better get back to work.
- Excuse me, Mr Jansen?

172
00:11:41,200 --> 00:11:43,668
Could I talk with you
a moment? In private?

173
00:11:43,702 --> 00:11:45,636
Oh.

174
00:11:46,655 --> 00:11:47,655
About what?

175
00:11:47,656 --> 00:11:50,402
I wanted to ask you
about that sale

176
00:11:50,442 --> 00:11:52,842
of those broodmares that my
mother stopped a few weeks ago.

177
00:11:52,878 --> 00:11:54,399
I know you and your brother aren't

178
00:11:54,400 --> 00:11:56,143
horse people and you
suffered a loss,

179
00:11:56,181 --> 00:11:59,617
but you don't need to worry
about this right now.

180
00:11:59,651 --> 00:12:00,777
Apparently, I do

181
00:12:00,819 --> 00:12:02,387
since they're my
father's horses, and

182
00:12:02,388 --> 00:12:03,913
the sale would've
been bad business.

183
00:12:03,956 --> 00:12:06,476
It's bad business to come to a
barn, interrupt a trainer's work.

184
00:12:06,496 --> 00:12:09,659
- Not if you want to keep him.
- I understand.

185
00:12:10,362 --> 00:12:13,297
- But about that sale?
- What about it?

186
00:12:13,332 --> 00:12:16,301
They were worth twice what we
were going to sell them for.

187
00:12:16,335 --> 00:12:18,565
I couldn't sleep last night,
so I checked the books

188
00:12:18,604 --> 00:12:20,663
and I made some calls
this morning to be sure.

189
00:12:20,706 --> 00:12:22,956
Like you say, I don't
own the horses.

190
00:12:22,957 --> 00:12:24,733
Your father has to sell them.

191
00:12:24,777 --> 00:12:27,109
But as trainer, you
would know their worth

192
00:12:27,146 --> 00:12:29,671
and that they were
about to be sold.

193
00:12:29,715 --> 00:12:31,792
I'm wondering why it
had to be my mother

194
00:12:31,793 --> 00:12:33,515
who stopped the sale and not you.

195
00:12:33,552 --> 00:12:36,316
The old man, your father? Ask him.

196
00:12:37,122 --> 00:12:40,353
I'm asking you. My father's been
sick for quite a long time now.

197
00:12:40,392 --> 00:12:42,257
You've been paid to look
out for his interests.

198
00:12:42,294 --> 00:12:43,978
And I do. Just because
this place is

199
00:12:43,979 --> 00:12:45,525
going downhill it ain't my fault.

200
00:12:47,299 --> 00:12:49,631
The sale was going to
be to Oakworth Farms?

201
00:12:49,668 --> 00:12:51,689
I learned this morning
that the owners

202
00:12:51,690 --> 00:12:53,399
of Oakworth were already talking

203
00:12:53,439 --> 00:12:54,761
about selling our horses for twice

204
00:12:54,762 --> 00:12:56,239
the price they were
going to pay us.

205
00:12:57,009 --> 00:12:58,490
You train for them,
too, don't you?

206
00:12:58,491 --> 00:13:00,009
I don't have an
exclusive deal here.

207
00:13:00,029 --> 00:13:01,708
I work for them
sometimes. So what?

208
00:13:01,747 --> 00:13:03,442
So if you arranged a deal

209
00:13:03,482 --> 00:13:06,417
that gave them four horses
at half their market value

210
00:13:06,452 --> 00:13:08,375
and they paid you
back, plus an extra

211
00:13:08,376 --> 00:13:09,944
share on everything they made,

212
00:13:09,988 --> 00:13:13,048
that wouldn't just be disloyal.
That would be committing fraud.

213
00:13:13,092 --> 00:13:16,186
Who the hell do you think you
are? Coming here, accusing me?

214
00:13:16,895 --> 00:13:19,420
Someone who knows enough
law to know she's right.

215
00:13:19,465 --> 00:13:24,129
And I'm not Missy anything. Get
your things and get off my farm.

216
00:13:24,169 --> 00:13:27,468
I have a contract,
and I'll sue you.

217
00:13:27,506 --> 00:13:29,587
If I ever even hear
your name again,

218
00:13:29,588 --> 00:13:31,499
I will see that you go to prison.

219
00:13:38,317 --> 00:13:40,217
Where does Bull Hancock eat lunch?

220
00:13:41,820 --> 00:13:43,720
At his club, every day.

221
00:13:45,424 --> 00:13:47,517
But it's gentlemen only.

222
00:13:59,738 --> 00:14:04,300
Miss? Miss, you can't...

223
00:14:04,343 --> 00:14:07,183
I'm sorry, Mr Hancock.
I told her this

224
00:14:07,184 --> 00:14:09,804
was a gentleman's
club, she just...

225
00:14:09,848 --> 00:14:11,873
it's all right, Brenda.
It's all right.

226
00:14:13,952 --> 00:14:15,817
Thank you, Seth. I apologise
for interrupting.

227
00:14:15,854 --> 00:14:17,879
It's fine. I have friends
here, Miss Chenery.

228
00:14:17,923 --> 00:14:18,981
Thank you.

229
00:14:21,326 --> 00:14:22,987
Well, how's it going?

230
00:14:24,563 --> 00:14:26,326
I fired Earl Jansen.

231
00:14:27,432 --> 00:14:28,524
Do tell.

232
00:14:29,334 --> 00:14:32,269
Does that mean you're selling
the horses or keeping them?

233
00:14:33,238 --> 00:14:35,832
The farm's in bad
shape, as is Daddy.

234
00:14:35,874 --> 00:14:38,900
But I'm not willing to sell it
unless I get what it's worth.

235
00:14:40,579 --> 00:14:44,276
Well, horse farm needs a
strong hand on the reins,

236
00:14:44,316 --> 00:14:46,717
but the hand that
threw Earl Jansen out

237
00:14:46,718 --> 00:14:48,878
the door looks
pretty strong to me.

238
00:14:48,921 --> 00:14:52,448
Well, I've got a
family back in Denver.

239
00:14:53,792 --> 00:14:56,556
I need a good trainer just
to get things stabilised.

240
00:15:00,832 --> 00:15:06,202
You need to talk to Lucien
Laurin. He's a French Canadian.

241
00:15:07,339 --> 00:15:08,829
Dresses like Super Fly.

242
00:15:09,575 --> 00:15:11,270
He's trying to retire.

243
00:15:12,878 --> 00:15:14,368
What do you mean, trying?

244
00:15:36,735 --> 00:15:38,032
Mr Laurin?

245
00:15:38,971 --> 00:15:43,101
Excuse me. I'm Penny Chenery,
Chris Chenery's daughter.

246
00:15:43,141 --> 00:15:45,410
And, I need a
trainer. Bull Hancock

247
00:15:45,411 --> 00:15:47,237
suggested that I find you...

248
00:15:47,279 --> 00:15:49,144
Yeah, Bull called
me, but I tell you,

249
00:15:49,181 --> 00:15:52,617
I'm tired of babysitting half-ton
animals who are nearly as stubborn

250
00:15:52,651 --> 00:15:54,881
and stupid as their owners are.

251
00:15:55,821 --> 00:15:59,382
I've lost interest in racing.
Don't even follow it any more.

252
00:16:01,293 --> 00:16:03,591
Well, I'm in a bit
of a tight spot.

253
00:16:03,629 --> 00:16:07,656
I wonder if you might just try it

254
00:16:07,699 --> 00:16:10,862
- for a few months and see how...
- I don't need to try anything,

255
00:16:10,902 --> 00:16:13,928
and trainers don't go anywhere
to work for a few months.

256
00:16:13,972 --> 00:16:16,209
They go where there
is a good horse.

257
00:16:16,210 --> 00:16:18,102
We have plenty of good horses.

258
00:16:18,143 --> 00:16:22,944
No, you don't. You have one or two
that might be worth the time,

259
00:16:23,649 --> 00:16:25,605
but you're a little
short on people

260
00:16:25,606 --> 00:16:27,779
over there who know
what they're doing.

261
00:16:27,819 --> 00:16:31,152
Well, that's why I've come
to see you, Mr Laurin.

262
00:16:31,189 --> 00:16:33,201
Miss, you're not
hearing me. A trainer

263
00:16:33,202 --> 00:16:34,955
makes his living off commissions.

264
00:16:34,993 --> 00:16:38,759
Ten percent off sales,
ten percent off winners.

265
00:16:38,797 --> 00:16:41,459
To get a top trainer,
you need a top horse.

266
00:16:41,500 --> 00:16:43,362
You're going to have
to go back to Bull

267
00:16:43,363 --> 00:16:44,992
and see if he has any other ideas.

268
00:16:45,804 --> 00:16:48,967
Mr Laurin, two of our mares
are pregnant by Bold Ruler

269
00:16:49,007 --> 00:16:51,237
who is the finest stallion
of his generation.

270
00:16:51,276 --> 00:16:52,766
- Fore.
- Hey.

271
00:16:52,878 --> 00:16:55,779
- Fore.
- Watch where you're hitting.

272
00:16:55,814 --> 00:17:00,046
Well, I yelled fore, you
idiot. That's what fore means.

273
00:17:04,089 --> 00:17:06,853
You see how I am, Miss
Chenery, when I put myself

274
00:17:06,892 --> 00:17:09,122
in a position to do
something poorly?

275
00:17:09,828 --> 00:17:14,629
And I'm afraid at your stable, I'd
be yelling fore all day long.

276
00:17:23,909 --> 00:17:25,968
Give my regards to your father.

277
00:17:46,198 --> 00:17:47,722
Fore.

278
00:18:37,983 --> 00:18:39,780
- When are you coming back?
- Soon.

279
00:18:39,818 --> 00:18:42,013
I need to talk to you about
this coin toss thing.

280
00:18:42,053 --> 00:18:44,521
- Coin toss?
- Jack, listen.

281
00:18:44,556 --> 00:18:48,754
Stallions cost more than mares.
No, they're more glamorous.

282
00:18:48,794 --> 00:18:50,728
But Daddy knew that a great horse

283
00:18:50,762 --> 00:18:53,230
comes just as much from
the mare as the stallion.

284
00:18:53,265 --> 00:18:56,393
He invested in mares, which is
the first smart thing he did.

285
00:18:56,435 --> 00:19:00,531
Second smart thing he did was he
made a deal with Ogden Phipps.

286
00:19:00,572 --> 00:19:03,097
Phipps? Richest man in America?

287
00:19:03,208 --> 00:19:06,075
Yes. Instead of paying a stud fee,

288
00:19:06,111 --> 00:19:08,040
Daddy made a deal to breed Phipps'

289
00:19:08,041 --> 00:19:10,309
best stallion with
our two best mares.

290
00:19:10,415 --> 00:19:12,735
When the mares are
close to term, they

291
00:19:12,736 --> 00:19:15,114
toss a coin to see
who gets which foal.

292
00:19:17,355 --> 00:19:19,619
That coin toss is in two weeks.

293
00:19:19,658 --> 00:19:21,477
What's the difference?
I don't have

294
00:19:21,478 --> 00:19:23,094
any idea which horse to choose.

295
00:19:23,128 --> 00:19:27,997
I've been through the stud books,
Jack. Bold Ruler, that's the sire.

296
00:19:28,033 --> 00:19:31,469
He was fast, but he couldn't
last over distances.

297
00:19:31,503 --> 00:19:34,631
Now the two dams are Hasty
Matilda and Something Royal.

298
00:19:34,673 --> 00:19:38,006
Hasty Matilda is eight years
old. She's still young.

299
00:19:38,043 --> 00:19:39,877
Since broodmares tend
to produce their

300
00:19:39,878 --> 00:19:41,970
best offspring while
they're young, that

301
00:19:42,013 --> 00:19:45,140
makes her foal the obvious choice,
since Something Royal's 17.

302
00:19:45,183 --> 00:19:47,981
But her grandsire
was Princequillo.

303
00:19:49,254 --> 00:19:50,585
He had great stamina, Jack.

304
00:19:50,622 --> 00:19:52,556
- Penny? Penny.
- Do you know what that means?

305
00:19:52,591 --> 00:19:55,822
- What?
- Sire and dam and Sam-I-Am?

306
00:19:55,861 --> 00:19:59,854
What is this? Come on.
We need you here, Penny.

307
00:19:59,898 --> 00:20:01,195
Come home.

308
00:20:03,401 --> 00:20:04,959
Right after the coin toss.

309
00:20:16,548 --> 00:20:18,914
- You about ready?
- We're ready.

310
00:20:18,950 --> 00:20:20,747
Excuse me just a minute.

311
00:20:27,025 --> 00:20:30,222
I'll be making the toss. Are
you waiting on anybody else?

312
00:20:30,262 --> 00:20:34,323
- No, I came alone.
- We toss right on the hour.

313
00:20:35,033 --> 00:20:36,694
- Good luck to you.
- Thank you.

314
00:20:39,437 --> 00:20:41,496
Hi. Good to see you, Mr
Hancock. How are you?

315
00:20:41,540 --> 00:20:43,098
Hollis. What are you doing here?

316
00:20:43,141 --> 00:20:45,200
I called Jack about
our tax issues,

317
00:20:45,201 --> 00:20:47,373
and he told me you
fired our trainer.

318
00:20:47,412 --> 00:20:49,846
How do you expect we can fetch
a good price on the farm

319
00:20:49,881 --> 00:20:52,372
if we don't have a training
operation in place.

320
00:20:52,417 --> 00:20:54,931
He was dishonest.
He had to go. You

321
00:20:54,932 --> 00:20:57,514
came down here because
of a trainer?

322
00:20:57,556 --> 00:21:01,253
This coin toss is big. The foal
could be worth a great deal.

323
00:21:01,293 --> 00:21:02,920
I checked with some
of Phipps' people.

324
00:21:02,961 --> 00:21:05,794
They think he wants
Hasty Matilda's foal.

325
00:21:05,830 --> 00:21:07,354
So that's who we'll choose.

326
00:21:07,399 --> 00:21:09,264
No, Hollis, I think that's wrong.

327
00:21:09,301 --> 00:21:11,185
Something Royal's
colt could have an

328
00:21:11,186 --> 00:21:12,964
unusual mix of speed and stamina.

329
00:21:13,004 --> 00:21:15,013
Phipps has the best
horse people in the

330
00:21:15,014 --> 00:21:16,770
world. You know more than they do?

331
00:21:18,209 --> 00:21:19,540
Come on.

332
00:21:24,916 --> 00:21:26,907
Please don't take
offence, Miss Chenery,

333
00:21:26,952 --> 00:21:31,082
but your father almost
never won our coin tosses.

334
00:21:31,122 --> 00:21:33,488
And I do hope you've
inherited his luck.

335
00:21:34,559 --> 00:21:36,584
All right. We're all here now.

336
00:21:37,295 --> 00:21:40,128
Mr Phipps has the call as
the owner of Bold Ruler.

337
00:21:40,165 --> 00:21:44,397
The winner has the choice of the
offspring of Mr Chenery's mares.

338
00:21:44,436 --> 00:21:47,371
Hasty Matilda or Something Royal.

339
00:21:47,405 --> 00:21:51,432
Are we all in agreement here?
All right. Here we go.

340
00:21:51,476 --> 00:21:52,841
- Call.
- Heads.

341
00:22:02,354 --> 00:22:05,721
Heads it is. I'll go
with Hasty Matilda.

342
00:22:07,392 --> 00:22:10,725
Miss Chenery. Please give
my best to your father.

343
00:22:13,331 --> 00:22:15,026
Well, that's that.

344
00:22:15,066 --> 00:22:16,533
But I got what I wanted.

345
00:22:20,438 --> 00:22:24,841
You got what nobody else
wanted. Time to go home.

346
00:22:28,847 --> 00:22:30,280
Can I give you a lift home?

347
00:22:30,315 --> 00:22:32,180
No, thank you, I have
Daddy's truck here.

348
00:22:32,217 --> 00:22:34,208
- All right.
- Bye, Bull.

349
00:22:41,626 --> 00:22:43,457
So, who won the coin toss?

350
00:22:44,429 --> 00:22:47,830
Phipps. He went
with Hasty Matilda.

351
00:22:47,866 --> 00:22:49,629
Of course he did.

352
00:22:51,569 --> 00:22:54,231
Call me when she's ready
to drop her foal.

353
00:23:04,783 --> 00:23:08,219
Pigs. Pigs. They're all such pigs.

354
00:23:08,720 --> 00:23:10,840
We've been putting on this
Protest Pageant for a year.

355
00:23:10,855 --> 00:23:13,335
Now the teacher says it's too
political and we can't put it on.

356
00:23:13,355 --> 00:23:15,122
What do you mean you can't?

357
00:23:15,160 --> 00:23:17,526
They have a rule that theatre
projects can't be political.

358
00:23:17,562 --> 00:23:19,105
When the teacher saw what we were

359
00:23:19,106 --> 00:23:20,929
doing... Dad, can
we, like, sue them?

360
00:23:20,965 --> 00:23:23,280
If you didn't disclose
until today, they

361
00:23:23,281 --> 00:23:25,425
couldn't be held
liable for a breach.

362
00:23:26,104 --> 00:23:27,867
What?

363
00:23:29,407 --> 00:23:32,376
Honey, listen. If this is really
important to you, you won't...

364
00:23:32,410 --> 00:23:34,241
- Tweedy residence.
- Is Miss Chenery there?

365
00:23:34,279 --> 00:23:36,190
Can we talk about this some more?

366
00:23:36,191 --> 00:23:37,191
Yeah. Ok. Fine.

367
00:23:37,192 --> 00:23:39,707
Penny. For Miss Chenery.

368
00:23:43,588 --> 00:23:45,613
- This is Penny.
- This is Eddie.

369
00:23:45,657 --> 00:23:48,421
Something Royal is about
to drop her foal.

370
00:23:49,561 --> 00:23:52,724
- All right. Thank you.
- Bye, Miss Chenery.

371
00:24:01,439 --> 00:24:03,339
Something Royal's
foal is on its way.

372
00:24:11,516 --> 00:24:15,782
Kick hard. Come on. Kick,
Chris. Come on. Good job.

373
00:24:17,255 --> 00:24:19,978
Hey, John. How would
you like to come

374
00:24:19,979 --> 00:24:22,557
with me and see a
horse being born?

375
00:24:23,361 --> 00:24:24,919
- Really?
- Yeah.

376
00:24:25,630 --> 00:24:27,154
Ok.

377
00:24:34,439 --> 00:24:36,430
How many times has she done this?

378
00:24:36,941 --> 00:24:39,273
She did it 13 times.

379
00:24:39,911 --> 00:24:41,538
You've done it four.

380
00:24:43,248 --> 00:24:44,545
Yes.

381
00:25:01,199 --> 00:25:04,635
It's a boy. It's a boy.

382
00:25:16,981 --> 00:25:20,576
- Have you ever seen that?
- No. Not me.

383
00:25:20,618 --> 00:25:23,348
- What?
- A colt stand up that fast.

384
00:26:01,092 --> 00:26:04,084
Hey, Daddy. I brought
you some company.

385
00:26:07,832 --> 00:26:09,857
This is the Bold
Ruler colt, Daddy.

386
00:26:17,075 --> 00:26:18,736
We call him Big Red.

387
00:26:38,997 --> 00:26:41,124
Let him run his race, darling.

388
00:26:50,675 --> 00:26:55,612
Flight 226 to Denver is ready
for boarding. Gate 33-D.

389
00:27:12,830 --> 00:27:17,460
- Almost done.
- I know this is hard for you.

390
00:27:17,502 --> 00:27:20,164
How long do you think you can
keep living two lives at once?

391
00:27:21,906 --> 00:27:25,307
The yearlings are looking
good, especially the red one.

392
00:27:25,343 --> 00:27:27,436
We've cut expenses.

393
00:27:27,946 --> 00:27:29,914
We're breaking even.

394
00:27:32,050 --> 00:27:36,146
I thought the point was to sell
the farm, not to break even.

395
00:27:38,389 --> 00:27:42,883
When I went off to college,
I felt like that colt.

396
00:27:42,927 --> 00:27:44,792
Full of promise.

397
00:27:44,829 --> 00:27:48,560
Full of adventure, like I could...

398
00:27:50,868 --> 00:27:52,495
make something work.

399
00:27:52,537 --> 00:27:55,165
I gave up a career to
have our family, and...

400
00:27:56,140 --> 00:27:59,576
this colt is part
of our family now.

401
00:28:00,712 --> 00:28:02,270
I just want to see him run.

402
00:28:02,313 --> 00:28:05,612
So after two years of
juggling all this...

403
00:28:07,085 --> 00:28:11,579
it isn't ending, it's
just... beginning?

404
00:28:32,010 --> 00:28:33,580
How's he feel, Jimmy?

405
00:28:33,581 --> 00:28:36,310
Just a big kid having
fun out there.

406
00:28:36,347 --> 00:28:39,475
He'll figure it out. Huh, Red?

407
00:28:40,518 --> 00:28:42,577
That's good. That's good.

408
00:28:42,620 --> 00:28:48,081
Now, listen, don't try to
change his natural gait, ok?

409
00:28:48,126 --> 00:28:49,787
Don't force him.

410
00:28:57,468 --> 00:28:59,698
Well, Mr Laurin,
what do you think?

411
00:28:59,737 --> 00:29:02,831
I think he's 1100
pounds of baby fat.

412
00:29:02,874 --> 00:29:04,535
He eats too much and too often.

413
00:29:04,575 --> 00:29:06,346
The only reason he
doesn't eat more

414
00:29:06,347 --> 00:29:08,067
is because he's too busy sleeping.

415
00:29:08,112 --> 00:29:13,072
He only does what he wants to do
exactly when he wants to do it.

416
00:29:13,384 --> 00:29:17,218
He lays against the back
of that starting gate

417
00:29:17,255 --> 00:29:20,224
like he's in a hammock
in the Caribbean.

418
00:29:21,059 --> 00:29:24,028
And when he finally does
get out of the gate,

419
00:29:24,062 --> 00:29:26,826
it takes him forever
to find his stride.

420
00:29:28,466 --> 00:29:30,195
Any other questions?

421
00:29:30,234 --> 00:29:33,465
I have one. How much did
you spend on that hat?

422
00:29:33,971 --> 00:29:36,337
Right now this horse
is all sleep and eat.

423
00:29:36,374 --> 00:29:39,502
But he's got fire inside
him. Ain't that right, Red?

424
00:29:39,544 --> 00:29:43,480
That horse couldn't beat a
fat man encased in cement

425
00:29:43,514 --> 00:29:46,210
being drugged backwards
by a freight train.

426
00:29:46,250 --> 00:29:48,775
Well, you should know, Mr Laurin.

427
00:29:50,388 --> 00:29:52,219
You thought that was
funny. I did, too.

428
00:29:52,256 --> 00:29:55,020
I wish we could just race
him under his name. Red.

429
00:29:55,293 --> 00:29:57,818
The Jockey Club insists
on unique names.

430
00:29:57,862 --> 00:30:00,194
I keep sending them, they
keep rejecting them.

431
00:30:00,231 --> 00:30:03,200
I've tried Something Special,
Royal Line, DEO Volente...

432
00:30:03,234 --> 00:30:04,667
DEO Volente. God willing.

433
00:30:04,702 --> 00:30:07,466
God may have been willing,
but The Jockey Club wasn't.

434
00:30:07,505 --> 00:30:12,807
Well, there is a race up in
Aqueduct in a couple weeks.

435
00:30:12,844 --> 00:30:14,931
I think we should
send him out. It's

436
00:30:14,932 --> 00:30:16,905
time. Not that I'm expecting much.

437
00:30:17,682 --> 00:30:19,013
Let's enter him, then.

438
00:30:20,151 --> 00:30:21,675
DEO Volente.

439
00:30:21,719 --> 00:30:24,415
- Well, that was really good.
- Can we be excused?

440
00:30:24,455 --> 00:30:25,581
Sure.

441
00:30:26,491 --> 00:30:28,925
- Please bring in the dessert.
- Ok, Mum.

442
00:30:29,560 --> 00:30:31,425
It's good you're home.

443
00:30:31,462 --> 00:30:33,930
Your daughters have something
they want to talk to you about.

444
00:30:33,965 --> 00:30:36,229
Oh? What's that?

445
00:30:36,934 --> 00:30:39,010
Kate and I were
thinking of going to

446
00:30:39,011 --> 00:30:41,030
Chile. Just for a
couple of months.

447
00:30:42,106 --> 00:30:45,132
Chile? What for?

448
00:30:47,445 --> 00:30:50,471
Teach English and learn Spanish.
It's part of a cultural mission.

449
00:30:50,515 --> 00:30:52,871
A mission to stir
up trouble and act

450
00:30:52,872 --> 00:30:55,418
cool, you mean? Chile
is socialist now.

451
00:30:55,453 --> 00:30:56,647
- Thank you.
- Go play.

452
00:30:56,687 --> 00:30:58,917
It is not. And that's
not why we're going.

453
00:30:58,956 --> 00:31:00,666
Although if an
opportunity to protest

454
00:31:00,667 --> 00:31:02,016
the war did present itself...

455
00:31:02,059 --> 00:31:03,458
See? This is what you're missing.

456
00:31:03,494 --> 00:31:06,224
Your teenage daughters are
growing up to become rebels.

457
00:31:06,264 --> 00:31:07,731
No, more like hippies.
Free spirits.

458
00:31:07,765 --> 00:31:10,359
Hippies are running from
paying the price of freedom.

459
00:31:10,401 --> 00:31:12,392
If there's a price, how
is it freedom, Dad?

460
00:31:12,436 --> 00:31:14,631
I'll answer that question
when you become an adult.

461
00:31:14,672 --> 00:31:16,663
Would anyone like some pie?

462
00:31:17,341 --> 00:31:19,036
- No, thanks.
- No, thank you.

463
00:31:19,443 --> 00:31:20,705
Well...

464
00:31:23,314 --> 00:31:25,748
When do you have to
give an answer by?

465
00:31:25,783 --> 00:31:28,183
There's a meeting for the
parents on the fifth.

466
00:31:28,219 --> 00:31:29,584
The day after my Protest Pageant.

467
00:31:30,488 --> 00:31:33,480
Your play? You're doing your play?

468
00:31:33,524 --> 00:31:38,086
Yeah. I present it as a civic
arts summer programme, so...

469
00:31:39,163 --> 00:31:43,691
Oh, Kate, after two years,
you're finally going to do it.

470
00:31:45,903 --> 00:31:48,064
Both of you can make it, right?

471
00:31:48,873 --> 00:31:51,398
The new colt runs his
first race on the fourth.

472
00:31:52,343 --> 00:31:55,779
That's in New York. I will
be on the first plane home.

473
00:31:55,813 --> 00:31:59,180
- Ok.
- Oh, by the way, Miss Ham called.

474
00:31:59,217 --> 00:32:01,515
Something about a
name for the horse.

475
00:32:04,555 --> 00:32:06,819
Rounding out the field
in the fourth race.

476
00:32:06,857 --> 00:32:10,884
Secretariat.

477
00:32:14,398 --> 00:32:16,628
Right up through there,
that one's ours.

478
00:32:16,667 --> 00:32:21,400
Let's take off this stupid...
Paul. Where's Paul? Paul.

479
00:32:21,439 --> 00:32:23,669
- Here. Right here.
- Listen.

480
00:32:23,708 --> 00:32:25,628
Quit sneaking around.
Got it? Listen.

481
00:32:25,629 --> 00:32:26,629
Yes.

482
00:32:26,630 --> 00:32:29,040
Watch out for number
six. He's got the speed.

483
00:32:29,080 --> 00:32:32,277
Also, watch out for number
three, who's going to hold back

484
00:32:32,316 --> 00:32:35,945
with five and eight along with
him. And watch out for number one.

485
00:32:35,987 --> 00:32:38,717
That's the best horse in the
field. Watch out for him.

486
00:32:38,756 --> 00:32:40,236
- All right.
- Where do you want this?

487
